author: @christopheroconnor5019
text:
It is amazing that such a good actor should appear in that insult of a film.

I watched it for its nostalgia value. Yes, the original is a silly 80s movie, but it is what it is. This one tried to be all things to all people.

He has a back story that is hinted at but never fully developed. Yep, a love interest that leads nowhere.

A badly crafted so-called emotional hook with the young teenage girl he meets, which is as thin as a sheet of bible paper.

The woman who owns the bar who hired him seems to be an afterthought, and how many seconds can they have her in it just to remind the audience to why he is there originally.

Every character is less than one dimensional. It seems as though the main star is going through the motions as if he was somehow obligated to do that film ğŸ¤”. Putting just enough effort into getting out of bed to make it to the set on time.

Then Conor turns up, playing a parady of himself with so-called dialogue that would be classed as Shakespearean in the world of chimps.

They also tried to make him funny with a little quip here and there.

It has special effects on the fight scenes. The question is why. Even those are clearly clunky as though they wanted to do away with actual stunt men.

Does start with potential but a quick steep drop into terrible.

text: It ain't Shakespeare, but it sure is fun. SPOILERS sort of. Excellent cinematography, the gags are top notch. I served in the Special Forces, I don't watch many action / war movies, I always get disappointed by the choreography, and especially scenes where there is the detonation and the hero calmly strolls away. Or takes out all the bad guys while they stagger around. When Dalton detonates the IED on the boat, gets blasted off his feet, hearing goes all wonky, he is disoriented. That is how it goes. Feels like you get kicked in the chest, and your brain is getting sucked out of your nose, hearing. Fights scenes top notch. Franchise anyone? Haven't seen Jake Gyllenhaal movies since The Day after, fun. ğŸ‘

But, even with all the CGI and location shooting in Dominican Republic, you can never duplicate the charm of the original.  Here's an idea: And Disney, are you paying attention? Don't remake the classic. Re-release it if you want. All good wishes.

author: @Kilroy_5150
text:
So, i was VERYskeptical about this movie considering i am an 80s guy and loved the first one. But....that's not a bad thing :)

Notice: Do NOT watch this movie expecting "old" RoadHouse....this is a re-imagining of it, a different story. You could even call it "alternate universe".

The action was much better than i expected and Connor MacGregor MADE this movie just as much as Jake Gylenhall did. My guess was that they had to train Macgregor "not" to knock Jake out by accident more than acting lessons . LOL This had one very "no holds barred" fights and a bunch of smaller fights.

Yes, they take a few quotes from the old movie....but that's it. So, again, don't expect the "old" movie.

It has a realy "Florida Keys" vibes but i really don't know "where" they filmed it.

But yeah, totally worth the watch. It could have been an early 2K movie but Hollywood is losing it's touch so lots goes to streaming channels.

Lol, you can tell that Joke didn't "memorize" a lot of movies that Patrick Swayze made. I watched a few interviews, he doesn't remember a lot of movie names :)

lol.

author: @bobhill3941
text:
I just watched this on Prime yesterday and thoroughly enjoyed. It still has the spirit of the original, but the creators ran with the concept and made it their own.

The original will always be special with Patrick Swayze and Kelly Lynch dancing to Odis Redding's "these arms" in the loft apartment, the fight scene on the river bank, Jeff Healey's amazing music, and of course Sam Elliot.

The remake was just as exciting, with it's slow burn intro, modern storyline, and riveting action. The fight scene was amazing, I loved the soundtrack, and the ending was surprising.

author: @arissarox
text:
The original is one of my comfort movies. I love it and I don't get sick of it. I was highly skeptical of a remake, even though I usually enjoy Jake Gyllenhaal. I knew he could do the action, but I doubted he could really replicate Swayze's zen Dalton. I'm really glad that's not what they tried to do. It seems like they are inspired by the original without trying to outdo it or redo it. At least from the trailer, it looks like a fun homage to a classic. Not all remakes are trash.

I think it was smart to lean into Gyllenhaal's innate sarcasm. I think McGregor is a fucking lunatic and it looks like he's essentially playing himself here, so... good casting lol. I'm open-minded about this after seeing the trailer. And Liman is right to be pissed at Amazon. This definitely deserves to be in theaters. It looks like exactly the kind of movie I would pay to go see in person. Total popcorn and friends flick.

author: @Mike.Cebert
text:
Yes I'm 40 and am a single Christian man, 6"2, bald but ok looking still, well travelled, level headed, sociable. Despite all this, it's been more than 8 years since I was properly with someone and that only lasted a few months. Time before that I was the victim of gaslighting and quite an abusive relationship going back 12 years now.

For several years now I've gone on dates and it goes nowhere because I'm generally not meeting women I find physically attractive because the ones I see on these apps aren't into me. I sometimes match with them but then no response. I guess as an attractive woman, they will always have so much more choice and get snapped up quick.

What's more, I am still a virgin technically speaking, despite having had multiple opportunities over the years with the few relationships I've had and then one off flings and "one night stands" which I really regret even going that far because it was wrong. But never had full intercourse. I wanted to save myself for marriage and do what's right before God but I guess the wife and the marriage never happened. I hope it's not too late but it's certainly getting to a point where I'm worried whether anything will change.

I understand that confidence and being content on your own is key, however I can't seem to shake off the feeling of failure and being unable to find and attract a woman that I want. Being on my own for so long, I can't see how it can be beneficial for anyone to be this way for this long and not have companionship. I don't mind being on my own, as I said I've travelled a ton, I've been to almost 70 countries now and the vast majority of that on my own.

author: @RandomAxeOfKindness
text: It looks like it could be good.  The editing doesn't floyd the action too much, the curse of modern Hollywood action scenes.  But it's more of an original film with little nods to the original, as the premise and plot really aren't the same.  The original Road House was a sort of resurrection of The Sheep Man (with Glenn Ford, Leslie Nielsen, et al), where the point is that the main character has done this a hundred times and generally knows exactly what the bad guys are going to do before they do it.  In this one, Gyllenhaal's a tough smart guy but a novice in the situation they drop him in.  Different kind of protagonist.  Should be fine.

author: @MrProy33
text:
This looks awful. The writers totally missed the point. We aren't supposed to know Dalton's backstory. He is a mysterious stranger, known only by reputation, like Chang, or Clint Eastwood's the man with no name. Maybe he is just a force of nature, come to life as an agent of justice. Or maybe he is a disgraced something or other... who knows! Other than that, all you gotta know is that somewhere along the line his badassery led him to being a roadhouse regulator, and all that matters is right effing now. There is no future, there is no past, just a tough guy in the present who promised to do some good in the world--and makes good on his promise violently.

That's why the original rocked. It borrowed from a rich history--the lone samurai. Plus the 80s stuff... totally hot chicks and over the top fights, obviously.

text: I could never understand the motivation to "re-make" a classic. The original had a lot going for it, including "originality", which is a concept Hollywood's clearly lost all touch with. All they've done here is to intensify every aspect and every character to such an extent that it comes off as yet another generic comic book superhero movie. That's all the industry seems to think matters anymore. The original had highly-developed, likable characters and as crazy as it got, it came from a foundation of reality. This new thing looks like a cartoon. I'll pass.

author: @HealthHorror
text: This is a prime example of why movies have lost traction the past couple of decades, because it mirrors a life full of arrogant, annoying people. In this, he is overly-confident and almost relishes in fights, as if they are so easy they are fun for him. In the original, he was confident and knew his power but did not flaunt it. He was wise but acted only when he felt necessary. He was humble. This new version is not so humble. And this is why movies are lackluster now. Characters are cartoonish and overly-arrogant or stupid or annoying. We went from a place of deep character development to one of superficiality overshadowing all that's holy.

author: @patrykdomanski9409
text:
Directors words: My plan had been to silently protest Amazonâ€™s decision to stream a movie so clearly made for the big screen. But Amazon is hurting way more than just me and my film. If I donâ€™t speak up about Amazon, who will? So here we go.

When Amazon bought MGM, one of the few remaining studios making big commercial films for theatrical release (movies like Bond, Creed) they announced that they would put a billion dollars into theatrical motion pictures, releasing at least 12 a year. They touted it as â€œthe largest commitment to cinemas by an internet company.â€ I can tell you what they then did to me and my film Road House, which is the opposite of what they promised when they took over MGM.

The facts: I signed up to make a theatrical motion picture for MGM. Amazon bought MGM. Amazon said make a great film and we will see what happens. I made a great film.

We made Road House a â€œsmash hitâ€ â€“ Amazonâ€™s words not mine, btw. Road House tested higher than my biggest box office hit, Mr. and Mrs Smith. It tested higher than Bourne Identity, which spawned four sequels. Iâ€™m told the press response has been Amazonâ€™s best since they bought MGM. Road House has a strong tie-in to the UFC, which has a rabid and loyal fan base that has spawned over 1.5 billion social media impressions for the film, and marketing hasnâ€™t even started yet. The action is ground-breaking. And Jake Gyllenhaal gives a career-defining performance in a role he was born to play. Audiences will want to see UFC mega-star Conor McGregor take his debut swing at Jake on the big screen. The reality is thereâ€™s nothing quite so fun as a good bar fight.

What else could I have delivered to the studio? Nothing, it turns out. Because contrary to their public statements, Amazon has no interest in supporting cinemas. Amazon will exclusively stream Road House on Amazonâ€™s Prime. Amazon asked me and the film community to trust them and their public statements about supporting cinemas, and then they turned around and are using Road House to sell plumbing fixtures.

That hurts the filmmakers and stars of Road House who donâ€™t share in the upside of a hit movie on a streaming platform. And they deprive Jake Gyllenhaal â€” who gives a career-best performance â€” the opportunity to be recognized come award season. But the impact goes far beyond this one movie. This could be industry shaping for decades to come.


/Deadline Â©ï¸

author: @SchulzEricT
text:
Well.... probably not a movie that should be re-made. Like "Red Dawn", like "Point Break", it's not like it's a great idea, it's a classic movie because something during it's execution worked, almost in spite of the dumb idea, that made it really fun. Re-makes should be about finding great ideas that weren't executed well; those movies are the opposite, it was all (or at least, mostly) about how the execution worked to elevate ideas that were, if not bad, still not very good, so that they were very good, fun, watchable movies. So... the "Road House" re-make is fighting an uphill battle to start.
THEN we have the classic "we need to show his backstory, how did he become a bouncer in the first place" trap that new movies love to fall into. No more starting in media res, we ALWAYS have to deal with the origin story these days. The 1st movie (in a planned franchise, rarely executed when the 1st movie fails to perform well enough to warrant a sequel... I wonder why) typically ends with the setup to the actual movie so that the 2nd movie is the actual movie (Mortal Kombat!). This trailer, as fun as it looks, seems like it's kinda setting that up, outlining that exact scenario.
SO... it looks fun, Gyllenhaal seems to hit the right note as Dalton, but man... I'm skeptical.

author: @LetsGetitBoah
text:
See this is what I like, if you're going to do a remake of a classic, do it your way. The ones that try to be like what came before them usually suck. Fright Night, The Fly, Oceans 11, Heat(most people don't know it's a remake of an 80's movie called LA Takedown), Dawn of the Dead, 3:10 to Yuma, True Grit, etc.

They honored the spirit of the movies before them, but added their own flavor without being disrespectful.

text: This remake, like the original, or a John Wick or James Bond movie, it's just for entertainment and not even close to real life.  These fighting movie fantasies are the biggest joke. In a country with the most gun deaths by far, people don't wait around to get their head kicked in.
